<br>
Tom;<br>
As far as verification of what the Quakers did in Nam, there are numerous accounts written in several books about what they did in Vietnam. Their own school supplies store will provide you with a list of their services in Nam. It's been sometime since I've read what others said about what they and other so-called good relief agencies did in Vietnam. What I do remember is the tons of rice we recovered from the enemy in the Arizona and dodge City territories. Burlap sacks with their socities name boldly stamped on each bags. I have pictures of those bags if you'll like. I also rremember how they worked along side of Catholic Nuns and German nurses at An Hoa in an area we were forbidden to go into, because they were medically treating NVA soldiers that had been wounded in battle. Every night the NVA would send some of their wounded to be cared for by them through a hole in the fence where we were not allowed to guard nor patrol nearby. Now, what kind of a war would have allowed that? Patch them up and send them back to kill Americans and we were not suppose to do anything about it, because they were American social organizations.  <br><br>
We learned early that if we were going to give canned food to a Vietnames family, we punched a hole in it so that they would have to eat it soon, otherwise it ended up in Charlie's backpack. 
<p><code>-- CB USA,  (Sparrowhawk) </code><p>


